Getting Started
Below is the simple "Hello, world!" example of a single value stream being subscribed using an observer function.
open Reaction.AsyncRx

let main = async {
    let xs = AsyncRx.single "Hello, world!"

    let obv n =
        async {
            match n with
            | OnNext x -> printfn "OnNext: %d" x
            | OnError ex -> printfn "OnError: %s" (ex.ToString ())
            | OnCompleted -> printfn "OnCompleted"
        }

    let! disposable = xs.SubscribeAsync obv
    ()
}

Async.Start main

asyncrx/Observers.html.body:
Observers
Observers (IAsyncObserver) may be subscribed to observables in order to receive notifications. An observer is defined as an implementation of IAsyncObserver:
let _obv =
    { new IAsyncObserver with
        member this.OnNextAsync x = async {
            printfn "OnNext: %d" x
        }
        member this.OnErrorAsync err = async {
            printfn "OnError: %s" (ex.ToString())
        }
        member this.OnCompletedAsync () = async {
            printfn "OnCompleted"
        }
    }

There is also a SubscribeAsync overload that takes a notification function so instead of using
IAsyncObserver instances you may subscribe with a single async function taking a
Notification.
let obv n =
    async {
        match n with
        | OnNext x -> printfn "OnNext: %d" x
        | OnError ex -> printfn "OnError: %s" (ex.ToString())
        | OnCompleted -> printfn "OnCompleted"
    }

